BUSINESS PROBLEM

  • Every day thousands of product reviews are sent to online retailers such as Flipkart "An e-commerce latform in INDIA".

  • Through these reviews, customers can freely express their thoughts, complaints and experiences.

  • Business cannot possibly read and comprehend so much crticism by hand.

  • Because reviews are unstructured data in the form of text , many important customer insights are lost

  • Business are unable to promptly recognize unfavourable comments and new problems

  • Pricing, customer service, and product quality decisons are frequently postponed

  • To make better decisions, a system that automatically evaluates customer sentiment from reviews is needed

PROBLEM STATEMENT

  • Flipkart product reviews provide indepth data about customer satisfaction and discontent

  • The majority of company just use their star rating, which truely does'nt represent customer sentiments and emotions.

  • Without automated techniques, text reviews are complex and challenging to evaluate.

  • Inconsistent, biased, and time-consuming is manual review analysis.

  • Positive, negative and neutral customer reviews are tugh to classify, specially the neutral reviews because they have certai kind of minor bias towards positive or negative.

OBJECTIVES

  • To examine consumer feed backgathered from Flipkart merchandise.

  • To use NLP techniques to preprocess and clean the raw review text.

  • To dtermine how each review express the sentiment of the customer

  • To categorize review as Positive, Negative, Neutral

  • To comprehend general consumer trends about various products.

  • To assist companies in raising customer happiness and product quality.

  • To illustrate how sentiment research might aid in e commerce platform decision making

PHASE 3 -TEXT CLEANING(PRE-PROCESSING)

REMOVING NOISE THROUGH REGEX AND IMPLEMENTING WHITESPACE TOKENIZER

Cleaning and preparing review material for sentiment analysis is the main goal of this part. When converting text to lowercase, it eliminates extreneous spaces, URLs, HTML tags, digits , emoticons, and mentions. For easier comprehension, emojis are translated into English. The text is made consistent and appropriated for additional NLP processing and model training by storing the cleaned summaries ina new coloumn.

In[]:
tokenizer = WhitespaceTokenizer()
def clean_text(text):
    if pd.isna(text):
        return ""

    text = emoji.demojize(str(text))
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r'http\S+|www\S+|https\S+', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'<.*?>', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'@\w+', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'[:;XO][-]?[")("DPp]', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)

    text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text).strip()

    return text


sample_n["Cleaned_Summary"] = sample_n["Summary"].apply(clean_text)

def generate_colored_wordcloud(text, title, color_func):
    wc = WordCloud(
        width=800,
        height=400,
        background_color="white",
        stopwords=STOPWORDS
    ).generate(text)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.imshow(wc.recolor(color_func=color_func))
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

MOST FREQUENT WORDS/N-GRAMS WITH STOP WORDS ONLY FOR VISUALIZATION

Using n-grams analysis, the most common word patterns from cleaned review summaries are extracted and displayed in this section. A count vectorizer eliminates, common stopwords and counts instances of unigrams, bigrams and trigrams to transform text into numerical features. To find the most frequently used words and phrases, the frequencies are combined and sorted. The top n-grams are then displayed in bar charts, which makes it simple to see frequently stated features, customer complaints, and reccurent product related terms. In addition to enhancing feature comprehension and supporting improved customer opinion interpretation for sentiment modeling for business insightss, this approach aids in discovery of significant linguistic pattern.

In[]:
sns.set_style("whitegrid")

def top_ngrams(text, ngram_range, n=15):
    vec = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=ngram_range, stop_words = "english")
    X = vec.fit_transform(text)
    counts = X.sum(axis=0)

    data = [(word, counts[0, idx]) for word, idx in vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=["ngram", "count"])

    return df.sort_values("count", ascending=False).head(n)
In[]:
def plot_ngrams(df, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.barplot(x="count", y="ngram", data=df)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel("Frequency")
    plt.ylabel("")
    plt.show()

PERFORMING POSTAGGING

Part-of-speech (POS) tagging are mapped to their respective word net categories using a helper function defined in this section. This section of code snippet transforms tags like adjectives, verbs, nouns and adverbs into an appropriate format because word net lemmatization requires particular POS inputs. During text prepration, the fucntion helps reduce words to their semantic base forms by improving lemmatization accuracy through proper POS mapping

In[]:
def get_wordnet_pos(tag):
    """Map POS tag to WordNet POS for lemmatization"""
    if tag.startswith("J"):
        return wordnet.ADJ
    elif tag.startswith("V"):
        return wordnet.VERB
    elif tag.startswith("N"):
        return wordnet.NOUN
    elif tag.startswith("R"):
        return wordnet.ADV
    else:
        return wordnet.NOUN
In[]:
def pos_tag_text(text):

    if pd.isna(text):
        return []
    tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    return pos_tag(tokens)

PERFORMING LEMMATTIZATION

In order to increase linguistic accuracy,this section lemmatizes the review text using Part of speech data. The word net lemmatizer transforms each word and its POS tag into its base or dictionary form. The resuting lemmatized text maintains meaning while reducing grammatical variances. Cleaner, more consistent input for sentiment analysis model is made possible by storing the preprocessed output in a new coloumn.

In[]:
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

def lemmatize_using_pos(pos_tagged_tokens):
    """Input: list of (word, POS) tuples  Output: lemmatized text string"""
    lemmatized_tokens = [
        lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, get_wordnet_pos(pos))
        for word, pos in pos_tagged_tokens
    ]
    return " ".join(lemmatized_tokens)

sample_n["Lemmatized_Text"] = sample_n["POS_Tags"].apply(lemmatize_using_pos)

EXPANDING CONTRACTION THROUGH TEXT BLOB

This section describes a function that expands the use of informal words and corrects typos in order to normalize review material. It automatically finds and fixes spelling errors that are frequently present in user generated reviews using Text-Blob. Robustness is ensured by managing missing values. This stage raises the quality of input data by increasing textual consistency and clarity, which improves feature extraction and produces more accurate sentimeny analysis results.

In[]:
def expand_contractions(text):
    if pd.isna(text):
        return ""
    blob = TextBlob(text)
    return str(blob.correct())

FEATURE 1- TF-IDF

The TF_IDF(Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) technique is used in this feature engineering stage to transform text into numerical features that are appropriate for machine learning models. In order to capture the significance of terms while lessening the influence of frequently occuring, less informative words, TF-IDF gives larger weights to words that are significant in a text but less prevalent across all publications.

With min_df =5 and max_df= 0.95, the vectorizer is set up to contain up to 8000 features, take into account unigrams to trigrmas, and disregard extremely rare or excessively common phrases. The model may now be trained using the converted training and test data (X_train and X_test)

In[]:

FEATURE 2- WORD2VEC

In this Feature engineering stage, text reviews are converted into numerical vectors with semantic value using WORD2VEC. While maintaining the sentiment distribution, the cleaned, tokenized reviews are initially split into training and testing sets. A Word2VEC model is trained using the training tokens to learn 250 dimensional vector represntation for each word in orderr to capture contextual relationship

X_train_w2v and X_test_w2v are the final fixed-length document vectors that are produced by averaging the word vectors of each review. These dense vectors improve sentiment classification performance by embeddingsemantic information that enables machine learning models to recognize connections, patterns and similarities in reviews

In[]:
def document_vector(model, doc):
    word_vectors = [model.wv[word] for word in doc if word in model.wv]
    if not word_vectors:
        return np.zeros(model.vector_size)
    return np.mean(word_vectors, axis=0)

X_train_w2v = np.array([document_vector(w2v_model, doc) for doc in X_train_tokens])
X_test_w2v = np.array([document_vector(w2v_model, doc) for doc in X_test_tokens])

def get_distilbert_embeddings(texts, model, tokenizer, device, max_len=128):
    model.eval()
    embeddings = []

    with torch.no_grad():
        for text in texts:

            inputs = tokenizer(
                text,
                return_tensors="pt",
                padding='max_length',
                truncation=True,
                max_length=max_len
            ).to(device)

            outputs = model(**inputs)

            cls_embedding = outputs.last_hidden_state[:, 0, :].cpu().numpy()
            embeddings.append(cls_embedding)

    return np.vstack(embeddings)

DEALING WITH DATA IMBALNCE - (SMOTE)

This data balacing stage(Synthetic Minority Oversampling TEchique) uses Sentence-BERT (all-MiniLM-L6-v2) to generate dense, fixed-legnth embeddings for every review that captures semantic meaning and context at the sentence level. By transforming text into numerical data suitable for machine learning algorithms, these embeddings preserve subtle linguistic connections that traditional approaches would miss. After applying sentiment labels to y, the embeddings serve as the feature matrix X.

THe class imbalance of the dataset is corrected using SMOTE. In order to produce balanced datasets (X_res, y_res), it generates synthetic cases for underrpresented sentiment classes. This improves generalization and predition accuracy by ensuring that models learn efficiently from each class.

y_pred_distilbert = np.argmax(y_pred_logits, axis=1)

y_true_distilbert = y_test_mapped.tolist()

accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true_distilbert, y_pred_distilbert)
precision = precision_score(y_true_distilbert, y_pred_distilbert, average='weighted')
recall = recall_score(y_true_distilbert, y_pred_distilbert, average='weighted')
f1 = f1_score(y_true_distilbert, y_pred_distilbert, average='weighted')
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_true_distilbert, y_pred_distilbert)
class_report = classification_report(y_true_distilbert, y_pred_distilbert)

print("=== DistilBERT Evaluation ===")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
print(f"F1-score: {f1:.4f}")
print("\nConfusion Matrix:")
print(conf_matrix)
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(class_report)

CONCLUSION TABLE

Model Accuracy Weighted F1 Macro F1 Deployment Ready? Notes
Logistic Regression 0.89 0.89 0.89 No Balanced, fast, interpretable, Although it has better accuracy bit still deep learning models are prefrable.
DistilBERT 0.73 0.71 0.36 No Poor on minority classes, Again thi s could be improved and then could be used on better dataset as this model was trying to overfit and learn, probably due to my synthetic balacing by SMOTE
DistilRoBERTa 0.94 0.94 0.80 Yes Excellent overall, minor class could improve, ok so finally comparing with others I could recommend this model for deployment as it managed to perform well considering the fact it had trained on synthetically balanced data by SMOTE

CONCLUSION

  • Through this project I made sure to sucessfully implement the sentiment analysis on flipkart products reviews with the help of one traditional and two deep learning models from hugging face

  • Logistic regression madee sure to give strong and stable performance which makes it suitable for baseline analysis

  • DistilBERT showed weak performance among all the three models most probably due to the sysnthetic balncing use SMOTE as the datset was extremely imbalnced

  • DistilRoBERTa turned out to be the pioneer with producing really high accuracy and balanced performance among all the sentiments

  • And considering the fact that data was highly imbalanced still DistilRoBERTa handled that synthetic data effectively.

  • So based on my journey of prepration and building this model I can recommedn DistilRoBERTa for real world deployment among the three

  • For future improvements I could only talk about two things one that larger real datsets could be use, or In my case - complete dataset, not the sample can be used and advanced imbalance techniques could be used.
